\begin_layout Standard
To demonstrate this, we investigate the existence of zero-energy solution
 (actually zero-energy, not just zero-eigenvalue) by solving 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}\bar{\Psi}(x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Additionally, and according to the particle-hole symmetry, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 is a solution then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{y}\tau_{y}\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\bar{\Psi}=\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

) is also a solution.
 Therefore, the only way to define a non-degenerate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{y}\tau_{y}\bar{\Psi}=\pm\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{y}\tau_{y})^{2}=-\mathds{1}_{2\times2}$
\end_inset

 imposed the constrain 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, fixing a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 allows one to define the reduced spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}=\left(\bar{\psi}_{\uparrow},\,\bar{\psi}_{\downarrow}\right)$
\end_inset

 using the constrain on the spin degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\psi}_{\uparrow/\downarrow}^{*}=\lambda\bar{\psi}_{\uparrow/\downarrow}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding reduced BdG equation can be reduced to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix differential equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-\eta\partial_{x}^{2}-\mu & V_{\text{Z}}+\lambda\bar{\Delta}+\alpha_{\text{R}}\partial_{x}\\
V_{\text{Z}}-\lambda\bar{\Delta}-\alpha_{\text{R}}\partial_{x} & -\eta\partial_{x}^{2}-\mu
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\bar{\psi}_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}\\
\bar{\psi}_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}
\end{array}\right)=0.\label{eq:BdG2x2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can then seek solutions of Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:BdG2x2}}$
\end_inset

) in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\psi}_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow/\downarrow}(x)\propto e^{\zeta x}$
\end_inset

 
